\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Response-adaptive designs were introduced following the ethical goal to
 maximize an individual patient’s personal experience in the trial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Another 
\series bold
important goal 
\series default
is to 
\series bold
maximize the power 
\series default
of treatment comparison.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These two goals 
\series bold
usually compete 
\series default
with each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Optimal allocation proportions are usually determined through some multiple-obje
ctive optimality criteria.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the situation when two binomials are compared and the measure of
 interest is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{A}-p_{B}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Optimal Allocations
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{p}_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{p}_{B}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding maximum likelihood estimators of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The allocation that minimizes the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{p}_{A}-\widehat{p}_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
Neymann Allocation 
\series default
with :-
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
They shift the allocation probability to better treatments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{n_{A}}{n}=\frac{\sqrt{p_{A}q_{A}}}{\sqrt{p_{A}q_{A}}+\sqrt{p_{B}q_{B}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An interesting fact about the 
\series bold
Neymann Allocation 
\series default
scheme is that for some values of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{A}\text{ and }p_{B}$
\end_inset

 it will assign more patients to the inferior treatment.
 Since, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{n_{A}}{n_{B}}=\frac{\sqrt{p_{A}q_{A}}}{\sqrt{p_{B}q_{B}}}>1\cancel{\implies}p_{A}>p_{B}\forall\text{ }p_{A},p_{B}\in\left(0,1\right)
\]

\end_inset

(which is obviously not desirable in terms of the ethical goal)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Optimal Allocations
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Another goal, a compromise between the ethical goal and efficiency, is to
 minimize the expected number of failures for a fixed variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{p}_{A}-\widehat{p}_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The optimal allocation for this goal is :-
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{n_{A}}{n}=\frac{\sqrt{p_{A}}}{\sqrt{p_{A}}+\sqrt{p_{B}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This allocation also has the advantage of allocating more patients to better
 treatment as :- 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{n_{A}}{n_{B}}=\sqrt{\frac{p_{A}}{p_{B}}}
\]

\end_inset

so it serves both the goals simultaneously which is much desired.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For more than 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 treatments i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

