status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Variability and Power of Using Adaptive Designs
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
When using response-adaptive designs in clinical trials, the number of patients
 assigned to each treatments are random variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore the power 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\text{rejecting }\mathscr{H}_{0}|\mathscr{H}_{0}\text{ false}\right)$
\end_inset

 (for most testing hypotheses and alternatives) is also a random variable.
 Here we generally consider hypothesis like :-
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathscr{H}_{0}: & p_{A}=p_{B}\\
\mathscr{H}_{1}: & p_{A}\neq p_{B}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The variability of allocation has a strong effect on the power.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Hu and Rosenberger show that the 
\series bold
average power of a randomization procedure 
\series default
is a 
\series bold
decreasing function 
\series default
of the 
\series bold
variability of the procedure
\series default
.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Variability and Power of Using Adaptive Designs
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The drop-the-loser rule has minimum variability (lower bound) in the class
 of all response-adaptive procedures targeting urn allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{q_{B}}{q_{A}+q_{B}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The doubly adaptive biased coin design can directly target any given allocation
 (may depend on unknown parameters).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At the extreme, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0$
\end_inset

, we have the sequential maximum likelihood procedure, which has the highest
 variability.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Variability and Power of Using Adaptive Designs
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 tends to 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

, we have a procedure that attains the lower bound of any randomization
 procedure targeting the same allocation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 becomes smaller, we have more randomization, but also more variability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Overall, the doubly adaptive biased coin procedure is the most favorable
 design as :-
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
It is flexible in terms of targeting any desired allocation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It can be applied to different types of responses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One can tune the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 to reflect the 
\series bold
tradeoff 
\series default
between the 
\series bold
degree of randomization 
\series default
and 
\series bold
variability
\series default
, and the tradeoff between 
\series bold
power 
\series default
and 
\series bold
expected treatment successes
\series default
.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
